You’re right to be concerned. The fact that print_plan() still shows leftover values is not automatically proof that deploy will run everything, but it is exactly the kind of UI confusion that can hide a real deploy-gating bug.

The key distinction is:

configure server --dry-run --mode pxe

is testing what the config would become, but it does not save that mode.

So if your saved config is still mode: full, then:

aerolitctl deploy server --dry-run

will still plan a full deploy. That part is expected.

But this is the real question we need to prove:

When saved mode = pxe, does deploy server only run PXE-related actions?
When saved mode = controller, does deploy server only run controller/NFS-related actions?

What I’d test next, safely

First, back up the current known-good config and generated vars:

cp -a /etc/aerolit/aerolitctl.yml /etc/aerolit/aerolitctl.yml.before-mode-test.$(date +%Y%m%d-%H%M%S)
cp -a \
  /opt/aerolit/aerolit-bundle/collections-hub/ansible/group_vars/all/aerolitctl_server_generated.yml \
  /opt/aerolit/aerolit-bundle/collections-hub/ansible/group_vars/all/aerolitctl_server_generated.yml.before-mode-test.$(date +%Y%m%d-%H%M%S)

Then actually save PXE mode:

aerolitctl configure server \
  --mode pxe \
  --interface ens160 \
  --server-ip 192.168.109.10 \
  --network 192.168.109.0/24 \
  --dhcp-start 192.168.109.100 \
  --dhcp-end 192.168.109.149 \
  --gateway none \
  --nfs-export-path /opt/aerolit/aerolit-bundle \
  --nfs-allow-clients 192.168.109.0/24 \
  --target-mount-path /home/unix/sysadmin

Then run:

aerolitctl status
aerolitctl deploy server --show
aerolitctl deploy server --dry-run

For saved mode: pxe, I would expect deploy dry-run to show PXE playbook actions, maybe interface/firewall actions depending your saved intent, but not Ansible controller playbook and not NFS export creation/service work.

Then test controller mode:

aerolitctl configure server \
  --mode controller \
  --interface ens160 \
  --server-ip 192.168.109.10 \
  --network 192.168.109.0/24 \
  --gateway none \
  --nfs-export-path /opt/aerolit/aerolit-bundle \
  --nfs-allow-clients 192.168.109.0/24 \
  --target-mount-path /home/unix/sysadmin
aerolitctl status
aerolitctl deploy server --show
aerolitctl deploy server --dry-run

For saved mode: controller, I would expect deploy dry-run to show controller/NFS actions, but not PXE playbook actions.

Then restore or save full mode again:

aerolitctl configure server \
  --mode full \
  --interface ens160 \
  --server-ip 192.168.109.10 \
  --network 192.168.109.0/24 \
  --dhcp-start 192.168.109.100 \
  --dhcp-end 192.168.109.149 \
  --gateway none \
  --nfs-export-path /opt/aerolit/aerolit-bundle \
  --nfs-allow-clients 192.168.109.0/24 \
  --target-mount-path /home/unix/sysadmin

What would prove deploy is wrong

If saved mode: pxe still shows something like this in deploy server --dry-run:

Would run ansible_controller.yml
Would create /etc/exports.d/aerolit-bundle.exports
Would enable/start NFS services

then yes, deploy is stepping on its own mode logic.

If saved mode: controller still shows:

Would run pxe_server.yml

then deploy is also wrong there.

What I would fix regardless

I would still clean up print_plan() now. Disabled sections should not look half-enabled. For example, PXE mode should show something closer to:

NFS/controller:
  Enabled : False
  Skipped because mode is pxe

instead of showing export paths, services, mount paths, etc. Same for controller mode:

PXE:
  Enabled : False
  Skipped because mode is controller

That makes the output much safer because you can immediately tell whether a section is actually active or just carrying saved/default values.